V'''Julia Driver''' is Professor of [[Philosophy]] at [[Washington University in St. Louis]]. She is the author of ''Uneasy Virtue'', ''Consequentialism'', and ''Ethics: The Fundamentals'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Julia Driver author page|url=http://www.amazon.com/Julia-Driver/e/B001JS94SG/ref=sr_ntt_srch_lnk_1?qid=1439555967&sr=8-1|accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref> as well as many articles in ethics and moral psychology. She is the leading proponent of a consequentialist approach to virtue theory.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Crisp|first1=Roger|journal=Philosophy and Phenomenological Research|title=Review|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/40040715?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents|accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref> Before coming to Washington University, she taught at Dartmouth College and Brooklyn College CUNY. She received her PhD from [[Johns Hopkins University]] in 1990, and her BA from the [[University of Texas at Austin]] in 1983.\u000a\u000aShe has received a Laurance S. Rockefeller Fellowship from Princeton University, a Young Scholar's Award from Cornell University's Program on Ethics and Public Life, an NEH Fellowship, and an HLA Hart Fellowship at Oxford University. She chaired the American Philosophical Association's Committee on the Status and Future of the Profession from 2012-2015.\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{Reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a* [https://philosophy.artsci.wustl.edu/people/Julia_Driver Washington University bio]\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Driver, Julia}}\u000a[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Washington University in St. Louis faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Johns Hopkins University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:University of Texas at Austin alumni]]
